Reference-contexts: Where cytology has not identified heteromorphism, gender appears to be determined by one or more major sex factors, and in some cases by the actions of many minor sex factors, (the terms are relative; reviewed in <ref> [Bul83, Ohn79] </ref>). In this paper we develop models relating to major and minor factor control systems, which we term multifactorial or polygenic. <p> The dynamics of multilocus or polygenic factors for determining organism phenotype have been widely studied <ref> [Win34, Wri39, Kos64, Wri68, Wri69, KL86, Bul83, Poe88, TB90, Nag93] </ref> and the effect of using such a system for sex determination has been studied in [Win34, Kos64, Wri69, KL86, Poe88]. <p> The second is where sex is purely genetically determined; the system evolving to one of two states where sex is determined according to the genotype based on one chromosome pair (sex chromosomes; [Ohn67]). These states (reviewed in <ref> [Bul83] </ref>) are male heterogamety (male is XY, female is XX; as in mammals) and female heterogamety (female is ZW, male is ZZ; e.g., birds). The third solution is essentially a combination of the previous two.
