Reference-contexts: under finite population assumptions the deterministic system evolves to one of three basic forms of stability: 1. monogenic purely random sex determination (all individuals genetically identical); 2. two factor pure genetic sex determination; 3. two factor mixed sex determination; with each showing a 50/50 sex ratio as we should expect <ref> [Fis30] </ref> in our sexually unbiased system. The non-deterministic system evolves into one of two solution types; either 1 or 3 of above. <p> Since 2a &lt; 4 there is no choice for the b value chromosome since b 20 with b + a 25. 2.2 How stability arises (Informally) Of note is the longstanding observation that sexual animals should allocate the sex of their offspring on a 50/50 basis <ref> [Fis30] </ref> 9 . This results from the observation that if the population has a biased ratio in favour of either sex then an animal can ensure a greater proportion of its genes will be present in the population in 2 generations time by producing more of the rarer sex. <p> The stable solutions of the system arise as the result of the interaction of two forces: 9 More preciseley equal resources should be invested in each sex 9 * the `rare female effect' <ref> [Fis30] </ref>; * probabilistic symmetry breaking. The first force is the result of departure from Fisherian [Fis30] sex ratio. If this occurs then the rarer sex will get to breed more frequently thus increasing its numbers in the subsequent generations. The second force results from the absence of selection. <p> The stable solutions of the system arise as the result of the interaction of two forces: 9 More preciseley equal resources should be invested in each sex 9 * the `rare female effect' <ref> [Fis30] </ref>; * probabilistic symmetry breaking. The first force is the result of departure from Fisherian [Fis30] sex ratio. If this occurs then the rarer sex will get to breed more frequently thus increasing its numbers in the subsequent generations. The second force results from the absence of selection. <p> The outcome is purely the result of two processes that affect factor frequencies in the gene pool. Random drift reduces genetic variability as a consequence of sampling error in finite populations [Wri68, Wri69]. Fisherian selection <ref> [Fis30] </ref> maintains only those combinations of factors that yield an unbiased population sex ratio; this latter process occurs as the rarer sex necessarily makes a relatively greater genetic contribution to the following generation.
