Reference-contexts: The dynamics of multilocus or polygenic factors for determining organism phenotype have been widely studied <ref> [Win34, Wri39, Kos64, Wri68, Wri69, KL86, Bul83, Poe88, TB90, Nag93] </ref> and the effect of using such a system for sex determination has been studied in [Win34, Kos64, Wri69, KL86, Poe88]. <p> Essentially the rate of drift is a function of effective population size, and the recombination rate is dependent on the degree of linkage of the genes. Traditional analyses of these complex systems assume that linkage is low [Bar86], however other authors <ref> [Wri68] </ref> suggest that linkage between related genes may be very high. However there are some observations that we can make dependent on the relative speed of the underlying rates in the system: * Recombination very much slower than drift. In this case our system will behave as before. <p> The outcome is purely the result of two processes that affect factor frequencies in the gene pool. Random drift reduces genetic variability as a consequence of sampling error in finite populations <ref> [Wri68, Wri69] </ref>. Fisherian selection [Fis30] maintains only those combinations of factors that yield an unbiased population sex ratio; this latter process occurs as the rarer sex necessarily makes a relatively greater genetic contribution to the following generation. <p> Within our process algebraic description is a very general evolutionary system which could be exploited to investigate problems of evolution other than sex. The effects of linkage and finite population size in evolution are known to be very hard to understand <ref> [Wri68, Wri69] </ref>. The process algebraic approach may give new insights in this area. 7 Acknowledgements Chris Tofts is supported by an EPSRC Advanced Fellowship (B/93/AF/1556). Melanie Hatcher is supported by an NERC Research Grant (GST/02/688). The authors thank Alison Dunn and Jonathan Adams for many useful discussions of this work.
